The game hasn't changed since probably 2015-2016. It's been about 10 years and most of the time only additions are new cases and skins. There was a time when I loved CS:GO and I enjoyed it a lot but about 5 years a go I realized that this game isn't what it used to be when it was released, instead it's a horrible game which introduces so many kids to gambling addiction. Even if we forget cases and skins there are hundreds of gambling websites, sure Valve shuts some of them down once in a while but they still keep many of those sites as it's profitable for them that those websites exist and gambling is there. I don't think many people realize how dark CS:GO is and what it does to young players who are so easy to pick up something new and well, gambling is up there. Other than that this game has been the same for 10+ years. If I wanted to play something competitive (even though I don't play Competitive games anymore) I would choose something else.

It was the late '90s, a time when the internet still buzzed with the sound of dial-up modems and cybercafés were sacred temples for young gamers. That’s where I first discovered Counter-Strike. Back then, it was just a Half-Life mod — a simple idea: terrorists vs. counter-terrorists. But for me, and for many from my generation, Counter-Strike was much more than that.

I remember my first matches on maps like de_dust and cs_assault. Games full of adrenaline, improvised strategies, and shouting between friends whenever someone pulled off an epic play… or died in the dumbest way. But it was also in those servers where I met the people who, without realizing it at the time, would become my best friends.

As time passed, we grew up. We studied, worked, moved away, some of us became parents. I now have several kids, responsibilities, a life that no longer revolves around spending afternoons at a LAN café. But one thing hasn’t changed: I still play Counter-Strike. Not every day, of course. Sometimes once a month, maybe twice. But always with the same friends. We log in, even if it’s just for an hour, and we’re back to being those kids from the 2000s — yelling through our headsets, laughing at silly moments, and coming up with absurd strategies that never actually work.

The most beautiful part is that now my kids watch me play, asking about that “old game” I like so much. Some of them have even started playing it too. I tell them that thanks to Counter-Strike, I have my best friends. That it was more than a game; it was a bridge between eras, a bond that’s lasted decades, a space where we’re still ourselves, no matter how much our lives change.

Counter-Strike didn’t just define a gaming era — it defined a part of my life. And as long as I can lift a mouse and hit the “buy AK-47” key, I’ll be there, in the server with my lifelong friends. Because some matches, simply, never end.

[h2] "CS2: I Came for Tactics, Stayed for the Psychological Damage" [/h2]
⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️
[b]
I installed CS2 hoping for tactical gameplay. What I got was a psychological thriller where the main antagonist is my own team.
[/b]

The lighting? Cinematic.
The maps? Beautifully detailed.
The guy on my team named “𝕍ₐₗₒяₐₙₜIs4Babies” solo-AWPs mid every round while blasting Russian hardbass through what I assume is a microwave. Truly inspiring.
[b]
Highlights: [/b]
[list]
   [*][b] Bullets only register after submitting a formal request to Valve HQ, [/b] with three signatures and a wax seal.
   [*][b] Smokes simulate real gas behavior. [/b] I don’t know what that means, but I can’t see anything and I’m dying - so it checks out
   [*][b] Molotovs create a realistic inferno [/b] that turns entire bombsites into hell. Still doesn’t stop five guys from rushing through it like it’s a mild inconvenience.
   [*][b] You can hear footsteps from a mile away, [/b] unless they’re behind you—then it’s a full stealth takedown with zero audio and full humiliation.

   [/list]
[/list]

 No aim down sights (ADS) except for scoped weapons (AWP, AUG, etc.). 
 Spray control is more rigid and requires significant practice to master patterns.

If you’re used to Valorant’s more forgiving movement shooting and ability to ADS with rifles, CS2 may feel raw but more “pure” in mechanical skill.
No abilities to cover mistakes  aim is king here.

Movement is slippery and very momentum based.
Bunny hopping, counter strafing, and pixel perfect peeking are high-skill areas.
No run/walk toggle 

Clean, minimalist UI and feedback. Not much visual clutter.
Gunshots and footsteps are louder and clearer, making audio crucial.

Rounds feel faster paced in movement but more deliberate in execution.
Economy is less forgiving. One round loss can snowball.

I didn’t know I was falling until I’d already hit the bottom.

Counter-Strike 2 started like any game. A match here and there. A few ranked games with friends. Some nostalgia. Some fun. But then came the skins. The shimmering, digital lottery tickets. I told myself, just one case. Just to see what I’d get.

I blinked and suddenly I was hundreds—no, thousands—of dollars deep.

I chased red skins like they meant something. I spun the digital roulette over and over, watching gold pass me by like a cruel joke. StatTrak numbers felt like validation. And when I finally landed a knife? I felt nothing. Just a momentary high, followed by the gnawing shame of checking my bank account and wondering what I could’ve done with that rent money.

I lied to myself constantly. This is the last one. I’ll sell this and break even. I traded dignity for pixels. I knew what I was doing—and I still clicked "open case."

But the worst part? I kept playing.

Even after the debt. Even after the friendships faded. Even after the joy became anxiety. CS2 had me. Not just with the gameplay, the endless ranked grind, the false hope of global elite. But with the cruel, glittering promise of luck. The skins became my obsession. My justification. My downfall.

Counter-Strike 2 didn’t ruin my life.
I handed it over willingly.

And I’ll probably log in again tonight. Just one more match. Maybe one more case.

Just one more.

CS2 is like a facelift that forgot the brain – visually nice, but dumb as hell

I wanted to like Counter-Strike 2, I really did. I’ve been playing CS since the days when your teammates would yell at you in internet cafés and call you a noob for not buying defuse kits. So when Valve said “Hey, we’re upgrading to Source 2,” I was like, okay cool, maybe we’ll finally get a fresh take on the game we love.

Turns out, CS2 is basically CS:GO Lite with RTX ON and a whole lot of things missing or broken.

The Good (yes, there’s some):

Smokes are sick now — dynamic and interactive. You can shoot through them and they react to the environment. Legit cool.

The game looks better. Cleaner maps, better lighting. Definitely prettier.

Gunplay still feels like CS… when it works.

It’s free, so I guess I can’t complain too hard, right?

But now the part where things get sh-tty

1. Hit reg is a joke.
You ever die, check the kill cam, and apparently you were aiming at the floor while your cross hair was glued to their head? Yeah. That happens a lot. And I’m not even talking high ping or potato net. Something about the tick system and sub-tick feels off.

2. Performance is garbage unless you're running a NASA PC.
CS:GO used to run on a calculator. CS2? My friend with a 1660 can barely hit stable frames on Dust 2 without his fans screaming for help. Huge stutters in fights, weird frame pacing, and GPU temps through the roof.

3. Where is the content???
No Danger Zone. No Arms Race. No proper Workshop support. Surf and KZ servers are either janky or straight-up gone. Even basic community servers are a mess. It’s like Valve deleted half the soul of the game and went “trust us, it’s better this way.”

4. Audio sounds like I have socks over my ears.
Footsteps are inconsistent. Sometimes you can hear the enemy from Narnia, sometimes they ninja behind you and stab you in broad daylight. Directional audio is scuffed and makes it feel like I’m playing underwater. I'm using Corsair HS80, btw.

5. Matchmaking is worse somehow.
Premier mode is just a weird knockoff of Valorant ranked. It doesn’t even show you actual ranks anymore. Also, cheaters are still a thing. The “new VAC” is apparently just old VAC in a new hat.

CS2 had the potential to be the next evolution of Counter-Strike. Instead, it feels like a downgrade disguised as progress. Valve took one of the most refined competitive shooters ever and turned it into a beta test with fancy lighting.

I’m not uninstalling (yet), nor will I ever do, I miss CS:GO. At least that game worked.

TL;DR:
CS2 looks pretty, smokes are cool, but the game feels like an unfinished mod with hitreg problems, bad performance, missing features, and weird audio. It's CS, but worse.

Valve, pls fix.

Counter-Strike is hands down the best competitive game ever made. It's simplicity allows balance that is virtually impossible to find in any other competitive game in the gaming scene. The combination of the needed individual skill, team communication and teamwork to play at the highest levels is unmatched. For a new player, Counter-Strike is probably a daunting experience at first. The amount of skill expression seen in Counter-Strike can prove to be a steep slope to tackle as an inexperienced player facing others with hundreds if not thousands of hours played. Stick with it and you will realize that it's not about anything other than your own technical skill, knowledge and ability to work with other players that is holding you back. However, it is not a perfect game. If you don't want to face cheaters, ever, then you will probably have to play via faceit or some other client, which will be extra challenging for new players. Another thing to point out is the importance of specifically teamplay and team communications to win games, which can be lacking in the lower ranks of CS and be a source of irritation for a lot of players who want to climb the ranks. Finding players who you have good chemistry with and playing with them is a good alternative, at any rank. Furthermore there is a big incentive to gamble in order to have cool looking gun-, glove-, knife- and operator skins, which I'm personally against. I only recommend this game to non-casual players. Sure, there are a lot of community made maps and servers and whatnot, which can offer a more casual gaming experience which I have personally spent a lot of time on but Counter-Strike really shines in the simple competitive format. Whatever you want to sink your teeth into, expect to spend a lot of hours to get the gist of it.

CS2: The Same Bomb, with a Fresh Blast.
🚩 Gameplay: Sweaty as ever. One tap or get tapped.
💣 Graphics: Smoke grenades now have PhDs.
🔧 Servers: Sometimes smooth, sometimes you teleport into 1999.
👥 Community: Still full of legends, trolls, and your new arch-nemesis.

I've played hundreds of hours in CS:GO, and CS2 feels like a love letter and a patch note combined. It’s sharper, shinier, and smokes react to wind now (finally!). But behind the new coat of paint, it’s still that same high-stakes, adrenaline-fueled, keyboard-breaking experience we love to rage at.

Ranked still gives you trust issues. Clutch still feels better than winning the lottery. And losing a 1v5 still hurts more than a breakup.

Is it perfect? No.
Is it Counter-Strike? Absolutely.

💥 9/10 — Bring your aim and a therapist.

CS2 Review: A Fresh Coat of Paint, But Is It Enough?
Counter-Strike 2 (CS2) is Valve’s long-awaited sequel to the legendary CS:GO, and while it brings some solid improvements, it’s not without controversy.

The Good:
Graphics & Engine: CS2 runs on the Source 2 engine, which gives the game a much cleaner, more modern look. Maps like Dust II and Mirage feel familiar but look sharper, with better lighting and improved textures.

Responsive Smokes: One of the standout features is the dynamic smoke system. Smokes now react to bullets and grenades, opening up fresh strategies and making gameplay feel more alive.

Tickless Servers: Valve’s new sub-tick system is meant to make hit registration more consistent. It’s a technical improvement, though some players still debate if it truly feels better in practice.

The Mixed:
Gameplay Changes: CS2 keeps the core Counter-Strike feel but makes subtle tweaks to movement and shooting. Some players feel it’s smoother, others say it’s clunkier. It depends on who you ask.

UI & Sounds: The new interface is sleeker but takes some getting used to. Weapon sounds and effects have been updated—some love them, others miss the old feel.

The Bad:
Performance & Bugs: At launch, many players reported FPS drops, stuttering, and bugs. Valve has been patching frequently, but performance still varies by system.

Missing Features: Not all content from CS:GO made it over yet. Some maps, modes, and community features are still absent, which makes it feel like CS2 isn’t fully done.

Final Verdict:
CS2 is a promising upgrade to a legendary franchise. It looks better, adds some cool tech, and keeps the core gameplay mostly intact. But it still feels like a work in progress. If you're a CS:GO veteran, you'll likely be torn between appreciating the improvements and missing what’s been lost (or hasn’t been added back yet).

Rating: 7.5/10 – Good, but still loading...

“CSGO2: Tactical Brilliance Meets Emotional Damage”

I’ve clutched 1v4s with 3 HP and a Glock. I’ve dropped 30+ bombs in Premier just to lose because Chad from Ohio can't hold B. Welcome to CSGO2—where aim is king, utility is art, and teammates are... character development.

Valve polished the gunplay to near perfection. Smokes feel like physics dissertations, and the sound design is crisp enough to hear your enemies’ childhood trauma through their footsteps. This isn’t a shooter—it’s a lifestyle.

Why I keep playing:

Flicking heads with the A1-S feels like therapy.

Outplaying a 5-stack with solo queue IQ is euphoric.

Hitting a no-scope mid with 0.5s left on the clock? That’s religion.

Why I need therapy:

Queueing solo after midnight.

Trusting comms in a global lobby.

The buy menu being slightly different still throws me off. Yes, it’s been months.

Every round is a new chapter. Sometimes I’m the hero. Sometimes I’m the villain. Sometimes I get team-flashed and nobody says a word.

CSGO2 isn’t a game. It’s an emotional rollercoaster strapped to an AK-47.
And I wouldn’t trade it for anything.

11/10—see you in Premier.

Counter-Strike 2 Review: A Tactical Evolution With Mixed Results
Rating: 7.5/10

After over a decade of domination by Counter-Strike: Global Offensive, Valve has finally released Counter-Strike 2, a long-awaited successor built on the Source 2 engine. While it brings undeniable visual upgrades and under-the-hood improvements, CS2 feels more like an overhaul than a true sequel—and that’s both its strength and its weakness.

Graphics and Engine Overhaul
The most noticeable change is the jump to the Source 2 engine. Maps are brighter, more detailed, and have improved lighting and physics. Smoke grenades now react dynamically to gunfire and environmental changes, introducing new tactical possibilities. Animations are smoother, and weapon models look fantastic, giving the game a modern feel without sacrificing its competitive edge.

Gameplay and Mechanics
Core gameplay remains unchanged—and for good reason. CS2 still thrives on precision, communication, and strategy. However, some mechanics have been refined. Movement feels slightly different (to the frustration of long-time players), and hit registration has seen improvements. Valve introduced subtick servers to enhance responsiveness, though the real-world impact has been inconsistent, and some pros argue that it hasn't lived up to expectations.

Maps and Modes
Classic maps like Dust2, Mirage, and Nuke return with visual upgrades, but many players miss popular community maps and modes that haven't yet made the transition. The lack of features like Arms Race, Flying Scoutsman, or custom servers at launch disappointed a portion of the community.

UI and UX
The user interface has been cleaned up and modernized. The new buy menu feels more intuitive and flexible, but also drew some criticism for breaking years of muscle memory. Stat tracking and player profiles are improved, but still somewhat barebones compared to what third-party tools offer.

Community and Transition
Perhaps the most controversial part of CS2 is how Valve handled the transition. CS:GO was entirely replaced by CS2, leaving players no way to revert. Many community servers, mods, and competitive leagues were disrupted. The game is still stabilizing, and updates have been rolling out to address bugs, performance issues, and balance concerns.

Verdict
Counter-Strike 2 is a promising evolution of the iconic shooter, but it feels like a work in progress. It preserves the tactical brilliance of its predecessor while modernizing its visuals and systems. However, rough edges, missing features, and a forced transition have made the launch rocky. If Valve keeps listening to the community and iterating, CS2 could easily cement itself as the future of competitive FPS. For now, it’s a solid—but not flawless—upgrade.

When I give this game a thumbs up, I give it that for people like me.

I'm an adult now, I've been around CS since I was around 11, back when CS:S was the main thing. CS:S was scattered in gameplay, didn't really have centralized matchmaking and actually trying to play the game as intended was difficult. I mainly messed around in gun game lobbies or TTT, and I mainly bought it to expand my Garry's Mod assets at the time.

Then CSGO came out, and with me being a teenager that liked shooting things I took a swing at it, and got started with Vanguard. I had played a lot of competitive FPS's up to that point but CS had hit the primal urge that all the others were born from. CSGO was in spirit the perfect sequel, and read this further if you want that to make sense.

Halo > Halo 2; H2 is regarded as one of the greatest sequels ever and the reason for that is that it innovated on already existing content of the original, added new content that kept up in spirit with the OG, and was an overall outstanding iteration on the original formula. In this sense, CSGO was the perfect sequel to whatever you could call the OG, whether it be CS:S or CS 1.6; or the combination of both (I'll let the monkeys argue over that in the comments.)

So, now I'm gonna circle back to what I said in the beginning, "When I give this game a thumbs up, I give it that for people like me."

CSGO had the innovation of proper loot cases (or whatever synonym you can come up with across other games), with skins that were unlike any other attempt at the concept (floats, wear, patterns, etc.), and this created a player-driven economy that the developers get to skim off of in their own self-created ecosystem. A concept that other publishers have tried to make poor imitations of in various ways (Just buying the skins, lesser forms of cases, etc.) In terms of innovation (or invention in this case) Valve knocked it out of the park. This is my problem though, I was 17 when I got into the game, and despite being well under gambling age, I definitely bought cases, keys, and spent many of my minimum wage fast food job paychecks fueling my desire to unbox a knife. In this aspect I think that being an adult now makes this more acceptable, but at the time not-so-much, there were better things for my 17 year old self to preoccupy himself with.

-------------------------------------------------------

This all aside, let's talk about CS2 objectively, and not from the rose-tinted glasses that many others seem to have over CSGO.

CS is one of those games that if it experiences even a minute change the community will collectively empty their bowels wherever they read the patch notes. In the car, at school, in bed, you name it, I can near-guarantee a passionate rant based out of hatred about the patch notes is soon to grace your eyes (even though they barely skimmed the notes and took to reddit to see what they should hate about it.) AK's and M4's must always be balanced this way, maps must stay predictable and anything new throws out their game sense. I'm not going to entertain these thoughts, a lot of the changes in CS2 are good, and resisting change in the first place is foolish. Everything changes, progress is constant.

The new smoke mechanics are astounding, and Valve is one of the first in the industry to attempt these new particle physics, I mean come on, people shooting through smoke giving away their location? Grenades clearing it temporarily? This adds new layers to the gameplay and most importantly the strategy, and like a perfect sequel it does it in amazing ways that doesn't compromise the spirit of what CS has going on for itself.

New additions to maps like Dust 2 have kept it interesting, the jump from CT to Cat is a great change, and it's a tasteful addition to the routes you can take to cat from A, mid, doors, CT, or even from car pushing back to CT should you not have the luxury of going down long to watch over the site. While a good portion of the community doesn't like this change, I'll tell them that it's not like they created a ladder going straight from the back of CT up to catwalk. The box jump takes time, it's risky, it's loud, and it really makes you vulnerable, the convenience to risk is balanced and that's what you have to look for when seeing if things like this are good changes.

At first I was hesitant about the armory passes, but I think that it's a good change of pace for monetization in CS. Battlepasses that aren't timelocked, you can redeem the points for a swing at anything in that dedicated store, you can have multiple of them, and the skins behind them aren't total dogwater either. Though I do wish they had stat-trak, I'm not gonna complain about a FN Long Dog should I ever finally unbox one.

The new lighting is mostly good, I think the CSGO art style was good don't get it twisted. After reviewing the before and after on Mirage for instance it is quite nice to have the inside of palace be lit up and not so dreary or dark. CS2 feels less like the source games of yore and has jumped forward with Source 2. The light bouncing and the vibes of the interiors of many of these maps has improved greatly with the new lighting. I did say mostly good, and this is because I do agree with others that it can be washed out in places. Right there at palace, the interior is nice, but once you walk out over firebox the plywood's detail is hard to see and the colors kind of blend together. I can easily see how this would cause some issues with gameplay, visibility, and being able to suss out the enemy. The skins are another issue, these skins were made for a darker world palette, and lighting too, so in cases of skins like a printstream the vibrant pearlescence is washed out and doesn't look as good as it did in CSGO. In a game where the skins are what make the majority of the money, this is problematic.

Though, I must say that the gameplay is still amazing, and the launch issues many complained about have mostly been rectified (mostly as in I can't find any of them anymore but I'm sure others will nitpick), subtick is still an issue but I don't really have this issue very often, like once every 20-30 games. It's non-consequential to me.

-------------------------------------------------------

CS2 is the perfect sequel to CSGO. The original core gameplay is here (as in nothing has been taken out), and the additions they've made have only made it better. New smokes are cash money, the map changes are pretty great too, the lighting is mostly good but struggles in other places (Reminder, Halo 2 was also like this but a bit worse in that dept.)

The reason this game is good for a person like me is that it has all the fixtures that I'd want, and that is appropriate for me. Skins/Gambling, who cares I'm in my late 20's now, I can make these decisions as a responsible adult. The strategy, gameplay, and patience required is ultimately the tempting aspects of gameplay that keep me playing it or bringing me back. The friends I play with, and the fodder I get to shoot at, are also some amazing things I enjoy about it. (Fodder as in: Impatient teenagers who hold W and don't like to think beyond 5 seconds ahead. Atleast that goes for most of you :^) )

Nostalgia vision is a bitch, and after seeing the content put out by others saying they grew up with CSGO, I get it man, I really do. I watched Halo go from peak to dogwater in a matter of a decade, I get the fear and hesitance that comes with change. The circumstances are different here, the game is great, the gameplay is fun, the skins are cool and the skills that you build here are to me pretty valuable in gaming.

CS is far from a "dead game" like many were saying before Armory pass update hit. Cheaters are everywhere and CS is unfortunately not an exception, but I am reviewing the game at its core before I am hit by a tirade of "cheaters bro cheaters" yes man, I get it, cheaters.

CS2 is a great sequel, nostalgic redditors be damned.

I still remember the first time I loaded up CS2, back when my children were laughing in the next room. The bright neon maps filled me with a sense of wonder I had not felt since they were toddlers chasing after soccer balls in the yard. Each round felt alive, every echo of footsteps carried the possibility of triumph or defeat. In that moment I was not just a player seeking a quick win, I was a parent soaking in a few spare minutes of joy before bedtime stories and bedtime prayers.

The core gameplay is as tight and precise as ever, with each shot carrying weight and intention. The maps are vibrant canvases where strategy and instinct collide in the best possible way. I still marvel at the smooth transitions between rounds and the way the community rallies around a clutch play. Even now I find myself searching for that spark of excitement that once lit up our little living room, and CS2 delivers it with startling clarity.

Of course it is more than just pixels on a screen. For me the game has become a living memorial to those moments when we shared laughter and simple victories. Whenever I log in I feel them beside me, cheering me on or playfully teasing my missed grenade toss. It is a strange comfort to know that even though they are no longer here, our shared passion lives on in every match I play.

Looking ahead I see CS2 growing stronger, evolving, and drawing in new players who will create their own memories and maybe some day look back on their own simpler times. The sense of community remains as strong as ever and I believe that this title will carry on for years to come, a digital gathering place where joy and skill join hands, and where memories—both happy and bittersweet—find a home.

At one point this was my thing but not anymore. If it's your thing still that's cool.

I was uninstalling this and the 80gb of storage space floored me enough to write this. The original was 20gb, for reference. There's so much bloat that it caused my face to twist when I realized how much space was wasted on a game I don't play anymore. And that was when I wrote this.

Like I used to have a lot of fun playing on the original (inaccessible still) CSGO, and all of the workshop maps associated with it. Lost to time now, most of them. I used to even enjoy competitive, quite frequently too (My record was Gold Nova Master before one of the great ELO/matchmaking changes). 

And I guess I got older, the game just makes me very angry now, frustration is a big driver for improvement here. But I can't say for sure what it is even that makes me feel so bad playing this game. I stopped playing roughly around when they changed most of the gun sounds, and there's been a truly extraordinary amount of updates since then. 

Source 2 is also a very impressive upgrade. However for my personal taste there's something now missing from the game visual style. It feels like 2006 again when every developer got access to the bloom setting and used it so often gamers got sick of it. The UI change feels weird to me and I can't navigate the menus anymore and I don't have the inclination as it is anyway to learn where all of the buttons went. 

It doesn't help that this game seems almost predatory. Skins, gambling, and real cash are permanently attached to the game now and it's been that way for a very long time. You certainly do not need them to play, but very often you will find people obsessed with skins and the skin market. I own some myself, some skins are quite pleasant looking and some offer stat tracking on the gun you have the stat track skin for.

And I deeply miss hosting my own servers and having my friends join to play Michael Myers, yknow? We'd get a bad comp match back then, and instead of going "we ball" or "run it back" we'd do something else in the game and cool before jumping back in. Now the game only feels focused on further developing this competitive community. Which I suppose is fine? Even though I feel a sense of revulsion anytime I meet someone who takes competitive CS2 seriously now, same extends to many competitive games. And I know that's a personal feeling. 

I think the only thing I can take away from this is something basic, the game will not remember the people like me who played it differently. It will not remember all of the workshop maps, either. Among the missing maps were heavily scripted stories, a bank heist, a fantasy where you slay a dragon. Gone. Because CS2 needed to replace CSGO. The developers decided that both could not co-exist and thus wiped the face of the workshop clean. 

The thing about those heavily scripted maps too was that I'm pretty sure the people that had made those were Russian. Those were made pre-war. Those workshop maps might be permanently lost, who knows what happened to the creator after so many years.

Remember this was Valve, by the way. Very well known for mod and community support at one point. 
It's also the same Valve that let Bethesda attempt to monetize the Skyrim workshop over a decade ago now, we shouldn't forget that either and remember who to hold accountable for mistakes like this. 

And I use mistake generously here. Sometimes it's not so easy to say.

Of course this entire review is based on memory, some relatively recent, I can't afford to give you a proper review of what the gameplay is like today, and it would date the review anyway. Neither can I truly explain the minutiae of how this game does not respect you nor your time. I want to say it uses the same method of keeping users that a social media platform does, keep the player irritated so that when they do improve the dopamine hits are enhanced. But that's speculative.

I don't think I've ever written a negative review for a Valve product. 
I've never felt offended by anything they've done up until recently.


Must be that I'm real sick of the way we've been going for the past decade now. Maybe someone else remembers, maybe I've lost it. 

I dunno, that's all I wanted to write.

It is everything but counter-strike. None of the other games from counter-strike series had childish play-doh graphics, and all of the other counter-strike games had different factions. You didn't even bother adding them.
What was the point of adding "water physics" in competitive FPS game? Agents blinking, seriously? Who needed random light solutions? Or pointless sparky-shiny interface? It all has led to severe FPS drop compared to CSGO, and it made new game having nothing related to CS but name. All that was needed from devs is anti-cheat. THIS is what you should add in competitive game. Not kids clay colors, not random details on maps. If I'd want to play random funny shooter, I'd go and play random funny shooter. I wanted to play counter-strike. Now there's nothing. 
This game was somewhat-military themed the whole time. Old maps were good and fit in this theme; new maps are just random colorsplashes. And valve had all the abilities to add maps from CSGO to CS2; they just decided not to. Visibility on dark spots on old maps could be improved by doing this exact spots lighter. Not by mindlessly recreating maps and oversaturating colors

Community is asking for factions or maps such as Cobblestone, Cache, etc? Nah, here are random maps from community workshop (that are not fit in the game theme again). Community is asking for operations? Nah, thinking is way too hard, so here's your battlepass. Community is asking for anticheat? What? What's this word?

You can play minecraft pvps instead of cs2 and you'll miss nothing, and you'll be playing with 10x more fps this way.

Unless counter-strike-called game has actual counter-strike atmosphere, i don't recommend it (if you care about what you're playing, of course). At the moment it's just generic shooter trying to clone {insert popular cartoonish shooters name}, and it's soulless af.

I’ve been playing Counter-Strike since CS 1.3, when jumping off a box felt like parkour and buying an AWP didn’t mean you were toxic... just rich. I've crouch-walked through dust in 640x480, sprayed through walls in aztec, and lived through the trauma of CS:Source’s hitboxes. And now, here we are — CS2. A whole new chapter.

Let’s be real — CS:GO was already a masterpiece. But CS2? It’s like your favorite band released a remastered album... and also added fog, volumetric grenades, and occasionally let you fly into the sky during a bug. Progress.

Watching legends like Heaton, Potti, elemeNt, fisker, f0rest, GeT_RiGhT, JW, s1mple, and ZywOo, now Donk evolve through these versions is like watching Pokémon evolve — only with more screaming and flashbangs. I’ve aged, my hairline has receded, but my muscle memory still bunnyhops (in my dreams, anyway).

And yes, CS2 is beautiful. The gunplay is crisp, the visuals are stunning, and the buy menu? Oh, the BUY MENU. Remember when buying a deagle meant you were smart and broke? Now it feels like Wall Street: buy this, rebalance that, swap mid-game... I didn’t realize I needed an MBA to afford a loadout.

Still, every bomb plant, every last-second defuse, every accidental team flash — it’s all still Counter-Strike. The chaos. The clutch. The community (and the occasional kid with a mic louder than a flashbang). This isn't just a game — it’s my youth, my rage therapy, and my aim trainer rolled into one.

Verdict: 10/10, would get one-tapped again for nostalgia.

Dlaczego Counter-Strike 2 to porażka stulecia:

Nie wiem, kto w Valve wpadł na pomysł, żeby zamienić złoto, jakim było CS:GO, na to... coś. CS2 to nie sequel. To downgrade. To jakbyś zamienił Ferrari na rower z urwanym łańcuchem i kółkami bocznymi. Ale okej, po kolei.

Silnik Source 2? Więcej jak SOUR 2, bo wszystko w tej grze jest kwaśne. Hitboxy? Jakby strzelać do duchów – raz trafiasz w nogę i robisz headshota, innym razem dasz serię w łeb i gość nadal żyje, bo "tickrate 128 na papierze, ale w duszy 30".

Ruch postaci? Jakby wszyscy mieli połamane nogi i biegali w basenie z kisielem. Movement z CS:GO był precyzyjny. Tutaj? Skaczesz jak chomik po energetykach, a bhop działa raz na pięć prób – i to przy pełni księżyca.

Dym granaty? Aaaa to jest dopiero kabaret. Te ich "dynamiczne smoki" wyglądają jak chmura z Vape’a nastolatka na TikToku. Do tego bugują się o wszystko – ściany, graczy, nawet o własne ego.

Menu? Zmienione. Na gorsze. Chciałem kupić M4 – przypadkiem wziąłem Negeva, bo interfejs wygląda jak z mobilnej wersji robionej przez stażystę.

Mapy? Wyglądają ładniej – i tylko ładniej. Bo gameplay leży i kwiczy. Dust2 świeci się jak reklama kasyna w Vegas, ale feeling? Zniknął. Mirage? Ciągle to samo, tylko teraz masz wrażenie, że patrzysz przez szkło powiększające.

Matchmaking? Czekasz 10 minut, żeby trafić na cheatera z flagą Rosji i teammatea, który ma mikrofon włożony do gardła i puszcza techno z Białorusi.

Optymalizacja? Jeśli masz RTX 4090 i procek NASA, może dostaniesz 120 FPS. Ale jak masz coś starszego niż 2023 rok, to powodzenia – gra ci się tak, jakby komputer próbował odpalić GTA VI na kalkulatorze.

The point of Counter-Strike is to compete in a team-based tactical shooter where two sides — Terrorists and Counter-Terrorists — face off in fast-paced, objective-driven rounds. The main goals depend on the game mode but typically include:
    Terrorists: Plant a bomb or defend hostages.
    Counter-Terrorists: Defuse the bomb or rescue hostages.

Each round ends when one team completes their objective or eliminates the opposing team. Winning rounds earns money to buy better weapons and equipment, which can give a strategic edge.
Beyond gameplay mechanics, the broader "point" includes:
    Skill expression: Sharpening aim, reflexes, and strategy.
    Teamwork: Coordinating with others under pressure.
    Competition: Climbing ranks, winning tournaments, or simply outperforming others.
    Fun: For many, it's just a thrilling, adrenaline-fueled game.

CS2 is everything I ever wanted from a sequel to a 20-year-old tactical shooter:

+ Better smokes
- Worse hitreg

The new engine makes the game prettier, sure. But also, my PC now sounds like it's trying to escape Earth's gravity.

Queue with friends, they said. It'll be fun, they said.
I queued solo once and came out with trust issues, a broken mouse, and a new philosophy degree from observing human behavior in Silver 3.

Pros:
+ Smokes now behave like real smoke.
+ You can still yell “rush B” and pretend it’s a strategy.
+ Guns still go bang.

Cons:
- Sometimes I die before the round starts.
- My team speaks only in riddles and slurs.
- The enemy team is always a five-stack of telepathic aim gods.

Final thoughts:
CS2 isn’t a game, it’s a lifestyle of disappointment and addiction.
See you tomorrow for another 4-hour session.

CS2 makes it to get me play ever so often since its release. The very unique skin market with high addiction risk yet has some major problems which are to be searched for almost 2 years since its release.

New maps, skins, stickers, ongoing esports all that is what the game has added with some minor tweaks here and there.

What the game reallly needs is well known since its release and yet nothing has been done which is to be really honest a really big shame.

To name a view:
1. I encounter not so many cheaters recently (past 6 month) but there are a lot out there. Overwatch should have been implemented from the start - Missing.

2. Subtick and 128 tick servers make the game up to date standards. At least it feels really clunky and is unsatisfaying to its core sometimes. Which is frustrating knowing games back from 2000 were better in Multiplayers. I believe if there are some limitations as the devs state, then the entire multiplayer coding of CS2 needs to be rewritten. As of now the system is at its worst - Missing.

3. Further modes, achievements or missions that make for some more grinding.

And so much more well known points.

Despite a lot of playtime at the moment. Subjectively there is no other option as to give it a negative review.
Maybe if they decide to make the multiplayer playable and the gameplay fluid again. That would be a great correction and I would change it from a negative to a positive.

I recently purchased Prime, and honestly, I regret it. One of the main reasons I was convinced to buy it was the mentioned of less  cheaters in matches. Unfortunately, that hasn’t been the case—in fact, it feels like there are more cheaters now than ever before.
It’s incredibly disappointing. I find it hard to believe that a game of this size and legacy still struggles to control such a widespread issue. Playing against cheaters makes it nearly impossible to enjoy the game or compete fairly. Over time, it just wears you down and takes the fun out of it entirely.
This game has been a huge part of my childhood and holds a lot of great memories for me. But with each match, that nostalgia is being replaced by frustration and disappointment. I truly wish more was being done to protect the integrity of the experience for players who genuinely care about the game.
In the end, you’re left with only two choices: either keep playing in a broken system where it’s nearly impossible to compete against cheaters, or be tempted to cheat yourself—risking a ban and the loss of your entire inventory. Neither option is fair, and neither is what this game should be about.
